            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Kian Reza\u2019s life is a symphony of flavors, orchestrated with meticulous care. The son of Iranian professionals who settled in San Jose before the revolution, Kian grew up between two worlds. His father, an engineer, instilled a sense of precision and structure, while his mother\u2019s kitchen was a vibrant realm of saffron, cardamom, and rosewater\u2014a place where hospitality was the highest form of art. While his parents hoped he\u2019d pursue a traditional career, Kian was always drawn to the energy and emotion of a shared meal.\n\nAfter earning a business degree from UC Davis, a post-graduation trip through Spain and Italy crystallized his calling. He saw how food was intrinsically woven into culture, history, and public life. This revelation led him to a graduate program in Hospitality Management on the East Coast. He honed his skills in the demanding, high-stakes hotel restaurants of New York City, but found the corporate environment creatively stifling. The turning point came when a headhunter called about a unique position: Culinary Director for a major San Francisco arts institution. It was the perfect fusion of his passions.\n\nNow at 39, Kian is at the pinnacle of his career. He lives in a sleek Hayes Valley condo, just a 0.9-mile walk from the institution he now helps define. His days are a blur of meetings, budget oversight, and his favorite part: creative development. He collaborates with curators to design menus for exhibition openings and works with local purveyors from the Ferry Plaza Farmers Market. His commute through the vibrant, boutique-lined streets is his time to decompress and observe the city\u2019s rhythm.\n\nKian shares his life with his partner, a landscape architect, and their social circle is a tight-knit group of artists, designers, and fellow food industry professionals. Though he has achieved significant success, Kian dreams of something more personal. His ultimate aspiration is to open a small, intimate restaurant that reinterprets the Persian flavors of his childhood through a modern, Californian lens\u2014a true homecoming on a plate, and his own contribution to the city\u2019s rich cultural tapestry."
