        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe\u2019s nine, perched on a stool in their San Jose home. His father\u2019s engineering blueprints are neatly rolled on the table, but Kian watches his mother. She cradles a few saffron threads like jewels, grinding them with a sugar cube. The scent fills the kitchen\u2014a fragrant, golden cloud of pure alchemy. In that moment, he understood there was a different kind of precision, one measured not in numbers but in color, aroma, and love. It was the first time food felt like art to him.\n\n2.\nIt was a tiny piazza in Seville, after his UC Davis graduation. He was 22, armed with a business degree he didn\u2019t know how to use. He watched a family share a simple plate of jam\u00f3n and manchego, their laughter echoing off the ancient stones. It wasn\u2019t a meal; it was a conversation, a ritual woven into the city\u2019s very fabric. He realized then that hospitality wasn\u2019t just a service industry. It was the connective tissue of culture, and he had to be a part of it.\n\n3.\nHe was 28, in a sterile New York hotel kitchen. The executive chef told him to use a cheaper, synthetic truffle oil for the risotto special. \"Make it pop for the investors,\" he\u2019d said. The artificial scent felt like a betrayal of everything he loved about food. That night, plating dish after identical dish, his passion dimmed under the fluorescent lights. He knew then he wasn\u2019t just cooking food; he was manufacturing a product. That feeling of creative suffocation cemented his resolve to find a different path.\n\n4.\nHe remembers the exact spot on Hayes Street where his phone rang. He was 32, interviewing for the Culinary Director position. The headhunter's voice confirmed the offer, and Kian stopped walking. He looked at the boutiques, the artful window displays, the mural down the block. It felt like the whole city was a gallery, and this wasn't just a job\u2014it was a curatorial role within it. For the first time, his disparate worlds of business, art, and food clicked perfectly into place. He was home.\n\n5.\nLast spring, at the Ferry Plaza Farmers Market with his partner. He was holding a basket of miraculously sweet, sun-warmed apricots, the scent transporting him back to his mother\u2019s kitchen. His partner, a landscape architect, simply said, \u201cYou should build a place around that feeling.\u201d Looking from the vibrant fruit to the Bay Bridge, Kian saw it clearly for the first time: not just a restaurant, but a space. A modern Persian garden on a plate, right here in his chosen city. The dream finally had a foundation."
